      number: 17,
      title: "After Lyra",
      content: "They did not reach the cave system. They were less than a mile from the first ridge opening, where old hydropower channels led into the Smoky Mountains, when the sky cracked. It was not thunder. It was not even noise in the usual way.\n\nIt was pressure, a low pulse that made lungs seize and vision flicker. Felix dropped to his knees, clutching his head. Reyna shouted, but her voice came out torn. Trees shivered. The mountain shivered.\n\nFinn looked up. And saw the new Legion. This was not a small patrol. Nor was it a tight formation. It was motion itself, a field made of metal. Hundreds of machines moved together so smoothly they seemed alive. Some walked on two legs. Others hovered on fan jets that scarred the moss beneath them. Their frames were lean now, shaped more like blades than beasts. Their optics did not glow red but pulsed in bands of white and green.\n\nThey did not hurry forward. They advanced with certainty. Finn grabbed Piper's arm. \"Run!\" She did not ask where. She did not hesitate. The group fled down a steep gully. Felix dragged the cart.\n\nReyna carried a child. Dell tossed a jammer puck behind them on instinct. It made a brief shriek, warbled, and died. That device meant nothing to these machines. They never slowed. A rail slug struck a tree beside Finn, splitting the trunk like paper. He yanked Piper behind a boulder. \"They have learned again,\" he panted. \"No echo, no weak point.\"\n\nPiper pressed the recorder into his chest. \"Take it.\" \"What?\" \"You can still use it. Maybe Felix can retune it. Maybe...\" \"Stop.\" His hands closed on her shoulders. \"I will not leave you here.\"\n\n\"You are not leaving me,\" she said softly but firmly. \"You will live, and I will make sure you can.\" Something exploded behind them. The ground trembled. Then everything happened at once.\n\nA scout drone swept into the gully. It was barely wider than a man's chest but bristled with white hot arcs. Its emitter turned toward the cart of cobalt cells. Piper did not hesitate. She blew a single note.\n\nA ribbon of white-green light lanced from the drone. There was no sound, only a flash brighter than lightning. In the frozen moment that followed, the world held its breath: leaves frozen in mid swing, mist caught like spun glass, Finn's pulse pounding in his ears. Piper remained still, recorder raised, mouth shaped for the next note that would never come.\n\nSmoke bloomed from her jacket. Her knees buckled. The recorder slipped from her fingers. Finn caught both at once but he felt only the weight growing lighter. He sank to one knee and pressed his hands against the wound that glowed too bright to take in.\n\n\"Keep it,\" she whispered, forcing the ribboned plastic into his palm. Her eyes met his and did not waver. \"I'm not afraid when I am with you.\" Then her strength left the world. Her hand went limp.\n\nSilence exploded around them. The Legion halted, optics flickering in confusion. But Finn saw only that small broken form in his arms. Shouts rose behind him as Dell and Felix battled their way down the slope. Reyna's voice cut through panic. But for Finn the forest no longer existed. He held Piper as if she were all that mattered. He walked, step by unsteady step, the hundred yards back to the cave mouth they had planned to reach together.\n\nInside, stone was cool against his knees. He laid her gently on a bed of pine needles, wrapped her in his coat, and placed the recorder on her chest. The yellow ribbon curled around her fingers like a final prayer.\n\nHe knelt in the darkness. The machines returned to their march outside, but he did not move. Tears did not fall, for they would not form. Instead a deep emptiness spread inside him, vast and certain. He closed his eyes and listened for her last note, a promise that he swore the world would one day hear again.",
